European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, Nazi occupation.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever—one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated—is a mistake.
That is like saying one part of a room could be heated while the other remains cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event elicits an echo across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to incorporate the new post-communist democracies—what is in Europe's interest—then a series of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a thriving society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepening and strengthening civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that the central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to the people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, communities, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy, with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call for vigilance.
To this evil one must respond as soon as it appears, but it is not enough for governments alone to act.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make quick decisions and to swiftly implement collective decisions—reforms that were deemed necessary by the recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of European security require interventions beyond the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate may not come, although an intervention would be in the interest of many people, of all of Europe, indeed even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological preparedness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, further measures are still needed in the field of preventive security, but even more is required so that this security reflects the values of the expanded civil society in Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted already at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was taken only hesitantly.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot remain forever dependent on the United States, especially not regarding European issues.
It must be capable of reaching agreements on its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of reaching agreement on means and methods to protect human rights, not only on its own territory but also in regions that may one day join it.
Such an EU expansion is only conceivable if it proceeds hand in hand with a bold reform of the EU institutions.
I am optimistic that the government conference on institutional reform will present feasible proposals for advancing the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting commitment to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
A related point concerning institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while at the same time adequately taking into account the size of each individual state.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber will not be elected directly, but will be chosen by the parliaments of the member states from among their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU — that is, the current Parliament — would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with an equal number of representatives for each country, would increase equality.
At some point, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution—a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution would require two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a constitutional framework would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Eurosceptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to better understand it, to see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
